**Problem 3(a)** Use the Cholesky factorisation to prove that the following $n Ã— n$ matrix is symmetric positive definite
for any $n$:
$$
Î”_n := \begin{bmatrix}
2 & -1 \\
-1 & 2 & -1 \\
& -1 & 2 & â‹± \\
&& â‹± & â‹± & -1 \\
&&& -1 & 2
\end{bmatrix}
$$
Hint: consider a matrix $K_n^Î±$ that equals $Î”_n$ apart from the top left entry which is $Î± > 1$ and use a proof by induction.


**SOLUTION**

Consider the first step of the Cholesky factorisation:
$$
Î”_n = \begin{bmatrix} 2 & -ðž_1^âŠ¤ \\
                    -ðž_1 & Î”_{n-1} \end{bmatrix} = 
                    \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix} \sqrt{2} \\
                                    {-ðž_1 \over \sqrt{2}} & I
                                        \end{bmatrix}}_{L_1}
                    \begin{bmatrix}1 \\ & Î”_{n-1} - {ðž_1 ðž_1^âŠ¤ \over 2} \end{bmatrix}
                    \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix} \sqrt{2} & {-ðž_1^âŠ¤ \over \sqrt{2}} \\
                                                            & I
                                        \end{bmatrix}}_{L_1^âŠ¤}
$$
The bottom right is merely $Î”_{n-1}$ but with a different $(1,1)$ entry! This hints at a strategy
of proving by induction. 

Assuming $Î± > 1$ write
$$
K_n^Î± := \begin{bmatrix}
Î± & -1 \\
-1 & 2 & -1 \\
& -1 & 2 & â‹± \\
&& â‹± & â‹± & -1 \\
&&& -1 & 2
\end{bmatrix} =
                    \begin{bmatrix} \sqrt{Î±} \\
                                    {-ðž_1 \over \sqrt{Î±}} & I
                                        \end{bmatrix}
                    \begin{bmatrix}1 \\ & K_{n-1}^{2 - 1/Î±} \end{bmatrix}
                    \begin{bmatrix} \sqrt{Î±} & {-ðž_1^âŠ¤ \over \sqrt{Î±}} \\
                                                            & I
                                        \end{bmatrix}
$$
Note if $n = 1$ this is trivially SPD. Hence assume $K_{n-1}^Î±$ is SPD for all $Î± > 1$.
If $Î± > 1$ then $2 - 1/Î± > 1$. Hence by induction and the fact that $Î”_n = K_n^2$
we conclude that $Î”_n$ has a Cholesky factorisation and hence is symmetric positive definite.

**END**

**Problem 3(b)** 
Deduce its Cholesky factorisations: $Î”_n = L_n L_n^âŠ¤$ where
$L_n$ is lower triangular.

**SOLUTION**

We can  write down the factors explicitly: define $Î±_1 := 2$ and
$$
Î±_{k+1} = 2- 1/Î±_k.
$$
Let's try out the first few:
$$
Î±_1 = 2, Î±_2 = 3/2, Î±_3 = 4/3, Î±_4 = 5/4, â€¦
$$
The pattern is clear and one can show by induction that $Î±_k = (k+1)/k$. Thus we have the Cholesky factorisation
$$
Î” _n = \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}
\sqrt{2} \\
-1/\sqrt{2} & \sqrt{3/2} \\
& -\sqrt{2/3} & \sqrt{4/3} \\
    && â‹± & â‹± \\
    &&& -\sqrt{(n-1)/n} & \sqrt{(n+1)/n}
    \end{bmatrix}}_{L_n} \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}
\sqrt{2} & -1/\sqrt{2} \\
 & \sqrt{3/2} & -\sqrt{2/3} \\
    && â‹± & â‹± \\
    &&& \sqrt{n/(n-1)} & -\sqrt{(n-1)/n} \\
    &&&& \sqrt{(n+1)/n}
    \end{bmatrix}}_{L_n^âŠ¤} 
$$



